Absa, Bidvest, Massmart, Merafe May Move: South African Equity Preview

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-08-01T22:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-01/absa-bidvest-massmart-merafe-south-african-equity-preview.html
The following stocks may rise or fall
in  South Africa . Symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last close.  The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index snapped four days of
losses, gaining 49.27 points, or 0.2 percent, to 31,257.31 by
the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  Absa Group Ltd. (ASA)  : South Africa’s largest retail
bank  releases results  for the six months to June 30. Shares in
the bank rose 1.1 percent to 132.95 rand.  Bidvest Group Ltd. (BVT)  : The National Automobile
Association publishes vehicle sales for July. The diversified
investment group with auto dealerships rose 2.6 percent to
160.92 rand.  Combined Motor Holdings Ltd. (CMH)  : The car
retailer’s stock was unchanged at 11.20 rand.  Imperial Holdings
Ltd. (IPL)  : Shares in South Africa’s largest auto dealer rose
1 percent to 116 rand.  Capital Shopping Centres Group Plc (CSCG)  : The U.K.’s
largest shopping mall owner reports results for the six months
to June 30. Shares in the company rose 0.5 percent to 41.10
rand.  Fortress Income Fund Ltd. (FFB)  : The South African
capital fund said in a trading statement that the distribution
per “B” linked unit for the six months to June 30 will be 35
percent to 40 percent higher than a year earlier. The stock
ended unchanged at 3.40 rand.  Massmart Holdings Ltd. (MSM)  : South African government
ministers including Trade and Industry Minister  Rob Davies ,
Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Minister Tina Joemat-
Pettersson and Economic Development Minister Ebrahim Patel brief
the media on the government’s position regarding Wal-Mart Stores
Inc.’s acquisition of a majority stake in Massmart. Shares in
the retailer rose 1 percent to 145.98 rand.  Merafe Resources Ltd. (MRF)  : The part owner of the
world’s biggest ferrochrome producer reports first-half
earnings. The stock closed unchanged at 1.08 rand.  Miranda Mineral Holdings Ltd. (MMH)  : The North Gauteng
High Court hears an application to place the minerals explorer
under supervision and commence business rescue proceedings.
Shares in the company climbed 29 percent to 45 cents.  To contact the reporter on this story:
